#text=I have a recipe for a yellow layer cake that I really like that came in my Kitchenaid cookbook .
#text=I use my Kitchenaid mixer to make it .
#text=It 's not too dry , and it 's not too sweet , which is why I like it .
#text=I took my mixer out of the pantry and set it on the counter .
#text=Then I found the right beater for cake and installed it .
#text=I creamed the butter and the sugar , added the eggs , and then added the wet and dry ingredients alternately .
#text=I had forgotten to take the eggs out earlier to let them come to room temperature , but it still works OK .
#text=While beating the cake batter , I preheated the oven .
#text=Then I took out two eight-inch round cake pans and buttered them .
#text=After that , I floured the cake pans and tipped the extra flour into the garbage can .
#text=When the batter was ready , I stopped the mixer , removed the bowl , and poured half the batter into each pan .
#text=I just eye-balled it and did n't measure exactly half .
#text=Then I scraped the remaining batter out of the bowl and into the pans .
#text=I put the bowl in the sink .
#text=I evened out the top of the batter a little with a spatula and tapped the cake pans on the counter to make sure there were no air bubbles .
#text=I put the cakes in the oven and set the timer .
#text=Then I turned on the oven light because I like to keep an eye on the cakes to see how they 're cooking .
#text=Plus it 's fun to see them rise .
#text=When the timer went off , I stuck a thin knife blade into each cake to test whether they were done .
#text=No crumbs stuck to the knife , so I removed the cakes from the pan and set them on the stove burners to cool .
#text=After a couple of minutes , I turned each pan upside-down onto a cooling rack and let the cakes cool for about an hour .
#text=Then I tipped one cake over onto a large plate .
#text=I made frosting and spread some on this layer .
#text=Then I tipped the other layer on top of that one and frosted it too .
